e career of Bishop Gregory of Tours, who benefited from the support of various patron saints and in turn promoted their cults. He then treats the political and religious dimensions of healing miracles--including their relation to Catholic theology and their use by bishops to challenge royal authority--and of pilgrimages to saints' shrines. The miracle stories, collected mainly by Gregory of Tours, appear in their first complete English translations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAeneid.  aAlternative medicine.  aAmulet.  aArchdeacon.  aAriamir.  aArianism.  aAugustine of Hippo.  aAustrasia.  aBaptism of the Lord.  aBrioude.  aBurgundians.  aBurial.  aCaesarius.  aCatholicism.  aChararic (Frankish king).  aChlothar I.  aChlothar II.  aChristianity.  aChurch Fathers.  aClergy.  aConfidant.  aConsecration.  aDeference.  aDesiderius.  aDysentery.  aEaster.  aEternal life (Christianity).  aExorcism.  aFalernian wine.  aFolk healer.  aFredegund.  aGenerosity.  aGeorgius.  aGod.  aGreat martyr.  aGregorius.  aGregory of Tours.  aHagiography.  aHelladius.  aHeresy.  aHis Family.  aHistorian.  aHumility.  aIntercession.  aJews.  aLate Antiquity.  aLent.  aLeprosy.  aLiterary criticism.  aLiterature.  aMagnus Maximus.  aMarmoutier.  aMartin of Tours.  aMartyr.  aMatricula.  aMerovech.  aMerovingian dynasty.  aMonastery.  aOld Testament.  aPaganism.  aPalladius of Saintes.  aPatron saint.  aPaulinus of Nola.  aPenitential.  aPersecution.  aPeter and Paul.  aPiety.  aPoitiers.  aPope Gregory I.  aPotion.  aPredestination.  aProcession.  aPutrefaction.  aRadegund.  aRelic.  aReliquary.  aRemigius.  aResurrection of the dead.  aRighteousness.  